import pyspark.sql.types as typ
labels = [
    
    ('RecordID', typ.StringType()),
    ('Default', typ.StringType()),
    ('Student', typ.StringType()),
    ('Balance', typ.DoubleType()),
    ('Income', typ.DoubleType()),
    
]
myschema = typ.StructType([
    typ.StructField(e[0], e[1], False) for e in labels
])
Default1 = spark.read.csv('/user/user1/Default1.csv', 
                        header=True, 
                        schema=myschema)

from pyspark.ml import Pipeline
import pyspark.ml.evaluation as ev
import pyspark.ml.feature as ft


df1 = Default1.select("Default_int", "Balance", "Income", "Student_int")

encoder1 = ft.OneHotEncoder(
    inputCol='Student_int', 
    outputCol='Student_int_VECT')

featuresCreator1 = ft.VectorAssembler(
    inputCols=["Balance", "Income"] +  [encoder1.getOutputCol()], 
    outputCol='features'
)

logistic1 = cl.LogisticRegression(
    maxIter=10, 
    regParam=0.01, 
    labelCol='Default_int')  # Response (dependent) variable: 'INFANT_ALIVE_AT_REPORT'

pipeline1 = Pipeline(stages=[
        encoder1,            # Stage 1: encoder (or data transformation)
        featuresCreator1,    # Stage 2: features creator (preparation of features or predictors)
        logistic1            # Stage 3: model
    ])

df1_train, df1_test = df1.randomSplit([0.7, 0.3], seed=666)


model1 = pipeline1.fit(df1_train)
test_model1 = model1.transform(df1_test)

%md
###	Explain the model performance
#### *Here we have AUC equals to 0.96 which means our model is performing very well and the True Positive Rate (The class lables that we assigned to Defaulted people was true and the same as our dependent variable value (Defaulted=Yes)) and it is high in comparision with False positive rate. Moreover, this is an unbalenced data and the number of defalted people are very few. Thats probably why our AUC is almost 1!
